# Memory Leaking in Rust with `Box::leak`

## What `Box::leak` Does

`Box::leak` converts a `Box<T>` into a `&'static mut T`, intentionally preventing the destructor from running and giving the value a `'static` lifetime.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::OnceLock;

// ============================================================
// Example 1: Static configuration loaded at startup
// ============================================================

#[derive(Debug)]
struct AppConfig {
    database_url: String,
    max_connections: u32,
    feature_flags: HashMap<String, bool>,
}

impl AppConfig {
    fn new(database_url: &str, max_connections: u32) -> Self {
        let mut feature_flags = HashMap::new();
        feature_flags.insert("dark_mode".to_string(), true);
        feature_flags.insert("beta_features".to_string(), false);

        AppConfig {
            database_url: database_url.to_string(),
            max_connections,
            feature_flags,
        }
    }
}

impl Drop for AppConfig {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // This will NEVER run when Box::leak is used
        println!("AppConfig dropped (you won't see this with Box::leak)");
    }
}

/// Leaks config intentionally to get a 'static reference.
/// Appropriate here because:
/// - Config lives for the entire program lifetime anyway
/// - We need 'static references for use in threads
/// - The OS reclaims all memory on process exit
fn leak_config(database_url: &str) -> &'static AppConfig {
    let config = Box::new(AppConfig::new(database_url, 10));
    Box::leak(config)
    // The Box is consumed, its heap allocation is intentionally "forgotten"
}

